Niphargus keeleri
is different from
N. hakani
in having a mandibular palp second article with 11 long setae (vs 6)ı third article with 19 D-setae (vs 15 D-setae)ı 5 A-setae (vs 2)ı 4 groups of B-setae (vs 2 groups) and 5 E-setae (vs 4 in
N. hakani
). Distal article of maxilliped palp has no setae on outer margin. Gnathopod I and II palmar spines are shorter than nail (vs as long as or longer than nail in
N. hakani
); gnathopod I with 2 small supporting spines on palmar corner (vs 3); gnathopod II with 1 small supporting spine on palmar corner (vs 2 in
N. hakani
); all segments of pleopods have long setae; distal article of uropod III exopod is short; telson has no spine on dorsal surface.

When compared to 

N. valachicus

ı 

N. keeleri

has a maxilla I inner plate of about 2/3 the outer plate length (shorterı about 1/2 the outer plateı in 

N. valachicus

); palp distal article has 3 long apical setae (vs 4). Pereopods III–IV have long dactyli without spines on inner margin or plumose seta on outer margin (vs 4–5 spines along inner marginı and 1 plumose seta at outer margin in 

N. valachicus

). Pereopods V–VII are long (vs short and strong in 

N. valachicus

)ı with long dactylus having no spines on inner margin nor plumose seta on outer margin (vs 3–5 spines along inner marginı and 1–3 plumose setae at outer margin in 

N. valachicus

). Postero-distal corner of epimeral plates I–III is slightly acuminated (vs sharply acuminated in 

N. valachicus

). Distal article of uropod III exopod is short (reaching 1/3 of first segment in 

N. valachicus

). Telson has no spine on dorsal surface.

